{{Nihongo|'''Ōtomo no Tabito'''|大伴 旅人||665 - 31 August 731}} was a Japanese [[:en:Kugyō|court noble]], military leader and poet. He is known for his military campaign against the [[:en:Hayato Rebellion|Hayato Rebellion]] and as the father of [[:en:Ōtomo no Yakamochi|Ōtomo no Yakamochi]], who contributed to the compilation of the ''[[:en:Man'yōshū|Man'yōshū]]'' alongside his father. He served as [[:en:Dainagon|Dainagon]] and held the [[List of Japanese court Ranks, positions and hereditary titles|court Rank]] of [[Junior Second Rank]].

== Life ==
Ōtomo was born in 665, the son of [[:en:Dainagon|Dainagon]] [[Otomo no Otomaro]]. His mother was Iratsume, the daughter of [[Kose no Hito]].

During [[:en:Empress Genmei|Empress Genmei]]'s New Year's Day celebration of 710, he led the cavalry, [[:en:Hayato people|Hayato]], [[:en:Emishi|Emishi]], and others as the [[:en:Shogun|Shogun]] of the Left with his deputy, [[Hozumi no Oyu]], in a march along the [[Suzaku Avenue]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |last=Ujitani |first=Tsutomu |title=続日本紀 （上） |publisher=Kodansha |year=1992 |at=和銅3rd year 正月1日条, 養老4th year 6月17日条, 養老4th year 8月12日条}}</ref>

In 711, he was given the [[List of Japanese court Ranks, positions and hereditary titles|court Rank]] of [[Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Grade]], and in 715, he was promoted to Junior Fourth Rank, Upper Grade, [[:en:Ministry of the Center|Minister of the Center]]. In 718, he was promoted to [[:en:Chūnagon|Chūnagon]], and in 719, he was promoted Senior Fourth Rank, Lower Grade.

In 720, when the [[:en:Hayato Rebellion|Hayato Rebellion]] erupted in [[Kyushu]] after the assassination of Governor of [[:en:Ōsumi Province|Ōsumi Province]] Yako no Maro, Ōtomo was ordered to lead Japanese forces to suppress the rebellion. After the death of [[:en:Minister of the Right|Minister of the Right]] [[:en:Fujiwara no Fuhito|Fujiwara no Fuhito]], Ōtomo received an imperial edict to return to [[Heijō-kyō|Nara]]. However, since the Hayato had not yet been pacified, the deputy shogun and his men were ordered to continue garrisoning the area.<ref name=":0" /> As a result, southern Kyushu was firmly brought under the control of the Imperial court under [[:en:Empress Genmei|Empress Genmei]].

In 721, he was promoted to Junior Third Rank, and in 724, he was promoted to Senior Third Rank upon the accession to the throne of [[:en:Emperor Shōmu|Emperor Shōmu]].

Around 728, Ōtomo was transferred to [[:en:Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu]] with his wife, Ōtomo no Iratsume, as Governor of Dazaifu, the second time he was sent to Kyushu after his 60th birthday, and this appointment could have been a strategic demotion by the four Fujiwara brothers, [[:en:Fujiwara no Muchimaro|Muchimaro]], [[:en:Fujiwara no Fusasaki|Fusasaki]], [[:en:Fujiwara no Umakai|Umakai]] and [[:en:Fujiwara no Maro|Maro]], to oust [[:en:Prince Naga|Prince Naga]], the [[:en:Minister of the Left|Minister of the Left]] in power at the time.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Nomura |first=Tadao |title=律令政治の諸様相 |publisher=Yoshikawa Kobunkan |year=1968 |at=神亀5th year  大伴旅人}}</ref> However, it has also been theorized that Ōtomo was transferred because of his excellent skills in diplomacy and defense in light of the international situation at the time.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Masuo |first=Shin'ichirō |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/37634692 |title=Manyō kajin to Chūgoku shisō |last2=増尾伸一郎 |date=1997 |publisher=Yoshikawa Kōbunkan |isbn=4-642-02310-0 |at=大伴旅人 |oclc=37634692}}</ref> In Dazaifu, he compiled the ''Chikushi Kadan'' of the ''[[:en:Man'yōshū|Man'yōshū]]'' with [[:en:Yamanoue no Okura|Yamanoue no Okura]] and [[:en:Sami Mansei|Sami Mansei]]. After arriving in Dazaifu, his wife died.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Man'yōshū |year= |at=巻5-795}}</ref>

In 730, he was appointed Dainagon.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Kuroita |first=Katsumi |title=新訂増補国史大系 Kugyō補任 |publisher=Yoshikawa Kobunkan |others=国史大系編修会 |at=大伴旅人}}</ref>

Tabito was a contemporary of [[:en:Hitomaro|Hitomaro]], but lacked his success in the Imperial Court. While serving as Governor-General of [[:en:Dazaifu, Fukuoka|Dazaifu]], the military procuracy in northern Kyushu from 728-730, Tabito hosted a [[:en:Hanami|plum-blossom party]], encouraging the composition of poetry among his subordinates in imitation of [[:en:Chinese poetry|Chinese]] style elegance. He also showed his Chinese education in his set of thirteen ''[[:en:Waka (poetry)|tanka]]'' in praise of [[sake]].

